data.text:
May 25, 1951 was a Friday and it was the 145th day of the year 1951 in the Gregorian calendar.

May 25, 1951 can also be written as 5/25/1951 in the US and as 25/5/1951 in UK and Europe.

The Zodiac and Astrological sign for May 25th is Gemini.

Gemini is the 3rd sign in the Western Zodiac. People born between May 21st and June 20th belong to the Gemini sign: discover Gemini personality and who should a Gemini marry.

Babies born in May are either Taurus or Gemini. People born before May 20th are Taurus, while people born from May 21st have the sign of Gemini.

Moon phase

The moon phase on May 25, 1951 was Waning gibbous.

The moon phase refers to the appearance of the Moon in the night sky on May 25, 1951 and is determined by the portion of the Moon's illuminated surface that is visible from Earth.

An observer located in New York City on May 25, 1951 at 10pm, would see the moon, being 63% full, rising at 12:25 am and setting at 11:09 am.

The previous full moon was on May 21, 1951 while the next full moon would come on Jun 19, 1951.

What is special about May 25th?

May 25th refers to a specific date on the calendar, which is the 25th day of the month of May. It is a date that occurs annually and is part of the Gregorian calendar, which is widely used around the world.

Over the years several events happened on May 25th, such as:

2019 - Saudi arabia-united states relations. iran-saudi arabia relations. iran-saudi arabia proxy conflict: u.s. president donald trump bypasses congress and approves the sale of billions worth of weapons to saudi arabia. he cited iranian threats against the latter.

2018 - Noblesville west middle school shootings: two people were injured in a shooting at noblesville west middle school, noblesville, indiana. one suspect is currently in police custody.

2017 - A booby-trapped package that was intended to be a gift for the former prime minister of greece, lucas papademos, explodes in his car in athens. his injuries are not considered life-threatening according to authorities.
